title: Grateful Dead Live at Giants Stadium on 1993-06-05
description: Hell In A Bucket, Sugaree, Wang Dang Doodle, Peggy-O, Eternity, Candyman, The Music Never Stopped > Easy Answers^> The Music Never Stopped Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain, Way To Go Home, Crazy Fingers-> Estimated Prophet-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Stella Blue-> One More Saturday Night, E: Box Of Rain

reviews.review_text:
Question I seem to remember a pre-recorded message from Mickey played before Bucket -- telling all the derelicts in Jersey that there had better not be any floor-crashing like the year before, lest the Dead be barred from future Giants Stadium shows. True? Or perhaps a figment of my imagination...other than that, pretty average show.

Also -- great Jersey moment I witnessed -- bunch of yellowjackets following a hesher into the men's room -- dragged him out kicking and screaming -- he had a six-pack of Budweiser tall-boys taped to the inside of his pants and he was PISSED that he was getting dragged out to his doom.

you are correct Old School Jersey The messages I remember were from Phil stating "you can't dance with a broken ankle, so please don't jump over the wall."  So funny.

That aside, the Sugaree is pretty hot, but other than that a very average show.
decent show Sound is superb! decent show. I just can never find my car at this venue. I usually have to wait until mostly everyone leaves.

Pre-recorded message from Mickey Yes...there was a pre-recorded message played a few times on the big screens from Mickey warning about crashing the floor, etc. I vaguely remember this first day as being crappy weather and the show not being too memorable. Jerry had some equipment problems, he was out before the first set trying to fix it and had to make a guitar switch at some point. Not a bad show...but not great.

6-5-93 Great 14 minute Sugaree. Great first set all around, pushing 4 stars. Scarlet>Fire is strong with Jerry really getting into his solos on Fire. Strong start to the East/Midwest Summer tour. 
O1 is strong. Stella is sloppy, and Jerry never sings the "Gonna Make 'em shine" line, due to the confusion and tempo issues. Sat Nite and Box are average.

Sounds is 5 stars all around. Crispy and beefy.

This was the debut of Easy Answers, strategically sandwiched between bookends of Music Never Stopped (to ease the pain!!).

Another nite in Jersey It was sly of the boys to slip Easy Answers into the middle of Music Never Stops.  Even so, knew I had another tune to add to the "hope they don't play it" list.  A list that didn't exist until spring tour 1980, and stayed Bobby and Jerry tune free until Liberty, Corrina and Easy Answers!!!!  In any event, first set was a great set for 1993.  Second started well, but the energy was definitely gone after Fire.... Still, there was no other way I would have chosen to spend an evening in the Swamps of Jersey!!!!

3 1/2 stars solid show. love the butchering of easy answers. You wonder why On the road agian, lazy lightning and lost sailor aren't good enough to revive but EA is played every other night. Those of you who got to see it played out of space must have been even more crushed thinking you escaped the horror. Pretty good show for 93 and the first set, sans EA, is particularly strong

Please Do Not Jump Over The Wall! A pre-recorded video message of Mickey was played  pleading with the hoarde to "Please do not jump over the wall" because hey, "You cant dance with a broken leg". Pretty bizarre for my first show...I cant believe I remembered that. 
Hey "Hugs Are Free" sister, you saved my life and Ill always remember you!
Peace

the band does something creative.... .....and all you can do is bash it. I'm so sick of people hacking on "Eternity", "Easy Answers", "Corrina" and "Liberty" I could puke. Bottom line is the band was coming up with NEW material, and sandwiching it between "Music" is just a creative way to get it out there. 

"Eternity" and "Easy Answers" took some time to grow on me (though i love them both now), and I loved "Corrina" and "Liberty" from the 1st time i heard them. "Eternity" is a simple but beautiful song writted with Willie Dixon and "Easy Answers" gets more depth each time its played and is now a song I look forward to (at Ratdog shows) since hearing the additions of Neil Young and Wasserman on the studio version and hearing Kenny Brooks add some depth with the sax. I would've loved to hear Branford sit in for this song. 

Anyway, 5 stars for the effort, and 5 stars for new tunes.
1 star for the unappreciative and excessively critical cynics.

Different from PA mix If you listen to the AUDs of this night, you can very clearly hear Healy messing with Bob's vocals on The Other One - on this mix it's almost entirely Bob's straight vocal, with faint echoes of the vocal processing at times.  Was this possibly an IEM mix for one of the band members?
Cannot believe this is '93 Sugaree through Scarlet-Fire are as solid as can be.

Jumping the Wall I remember the pre-recorded messages from the band saying "Dont jump over the wall". Thats because the year before in '92 it was like somebody unleashed the flood gates and everybody seated in the lower tier just poured over the wall. I remember my sister, my buddy & I working our way down to a fence that was lined up with cops and we just all pushed the cops out of the way, ran down to the wall and jumped. It was a pretty good drop and as soon as you hit the ground you had to run because the cops & security were all over you. Needless to say I am Grateful to of had friends like Chris Boswell who took me to my 1st show.  Good Times!!!

Some tasty moments I had really good floor seats for this show, but musically it didn't stick into my brain much. On relistening, I found that there's some great moments, though the energy levels and performance slide a bit as the second set goes on.

This is definitely an ear monitor mix, as Jerry can be heard saying “My guitar’s doing that thing again” about two minutes into Music.

Both Eternity and Sugaree are very strong versions. Sticking the debut of Easy Answers into Music was a surprise move. As we know, this wasn’t one of Bobby’s more popular tunes the last three years of the band.  I like the fuzzy guitar, but get annoyed by the jarring delivery. The return to Music is less jarring, and the band picks up the set closer nicely.  We even get some brief trilling from Jerry. 

The second set starts off on great footing with a tight Scarlet>Fire, but loses steam with the one-two punch of Way to Go and Crazy Fingers.

Both Estimated and the Other One are solid performances, but the rest of the show doesn't rise above average.

Guy jumped off 3rd tier You are correct. Funny I was just listening on XM to Music never stopped>easy answers.and decided to verify this was the same show they played Estimated and the guy jumped. Phil's side I was one section down from him about 5 rows back i remember it being during Estimated which was right before D/S. My recollection is he jumped right when they sang rising up to paradise because I thought how tripping must he have been to surreal and yes he seemed to be floating there.

6/5/93 thought I would float away with the weather I too was at this show.  I have never been so wet.  I did not see the guy float off the 3rd tier, as I was on the floor close to the stage.  I loved this show, although I think it took me like 2 hours to get out of the parking lot.  I don't think my sneakers dried out for a week. It was the better show of the 2, but the weather was much kinder on Sunday.

I am the Giant Stadium Jumper That was me.
It was first song second set. I didnt think i could fly, I thought I could clear it. Dodging security 
was pretty Lucy blinded that evening. First show of the summer tour, midwest boy, runaway w Jerry and livin on the west coast. HELLO cosmic school.
I broke my legs in 23 places (18 & 5)
made the rest of tour, cut my cast off after the last show up in an Oregon reservoir.
Stil hangin  in Chico, Still tour music all sumer long! LONG LIVE LIVE MUSIC!!!! 

facebook-Bradleybasshead

To the jumper... If you were the jumper, thanks for ruining an otherwise good show for many people. I didn't see you take the leap, but many of us in our section were so concerned that someone was seriously injured or killed that we were bummed out the rest of the show. It was the 1st time I couldn't get into Scarlet>Fire. I didn't see it happen, but we could see all the Emergency personnel working on you and the person you hot most of the 2nd set.
Average 93 Highlights: Sugaree

HEY NOW Great show music into answers back to music pretty killer and it’s the first ever easy answers pretty great. The sugaree is real good just soars and Vince is on this whole night. The Scarlett fire is absolute 🔥 love this show I love 93 seriously underrated time.

dreary weekend So I went to both show and it was a rainy week end which effected my mood somewhat along with the fact that my car wouldn't start from the night before and was still in a Giant puddle. So I had things on my mind other than the show. I was just OK with the show at the time. I am glad that it was recorded so I can listen to it again all these years later though. It sounds better after the fact.

My very first show I often used to not remember if it was 94 or 93, well I know it was 1993.  I remember we did not go inside the stadium until after Sting played.   I drove down with a good friend of mine back then in his VW bus to buy pre sale tickets after standing in line in NJ at a random ticket outlet doing the lottery draw. 
After buying tickets months went by until we all rode in a van packed to go back down to NJ together.  John, Twit, Mike, Doug, me and everyone's girlfriends.  I did not have a ticket to the second night so I hung in the minivan. It rained half the time we were there.    My seat was in an upper tier my friends that I went with had seats somewhere else since we made separate purchases.  I have listened and been a fan of the Grateful Dead ever since.  I was fortunate enough to get to see Jerry one more time the following year in Madison Square Gardens.  Some of those other friends went on to tour with the Dead to see 100's of shows.  Mike caught a lot of local shows with 400 miles, Twit and John both toured.  I wanted to take that journey as well but I wasn't able to.  I was able to see one more show the next year at Madison Square Gardens.  I was able to score a very good seat at my 2nd Dead show.  Mail order was the way to get the good seats I found out!  Cheers!
